se (<i>c.</i> 1750–1808) came from Scotland(probably Kilmarnock) to Edgefield, SC, <i>c.</i> 1770."]},{"name":"Gilchrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilkerson","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chrìosd</i> ‘son of <i>Gille Chrìosd</i>' (see   Gilchrist  )."]},{"name":"Gilkey","meanings":["Irish (northern): possibly a pet form of the Scottishpersonal name   Gilchrist  ."]},{"name":"Gilcrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilcrease","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Gilchrist Earl of Angus was born in 1136. He married Elizabeth De Menteith in 1181. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1211, in Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1136–1211":"1136–1211","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1136":"1136",